      "author_association" : "CONTRIBUTOR",
      "body" : "\n\nOn November 5, 2022 11:27:55 AM GMT+01:00, \"Niklas GÃ¶gge\" ***@***.***> wrote:\n>Concept ACK\n>\n>It's kinda dumb that the full RBF discussion is stalling the release. We have not had `mempoolfullrbf` for ten+ years, surely not having it for one or two more releases is not a problem. `mempoolfullrbf` has also not been shipped yet, so \"removing\" it does no harm what so ever. The amount of time being wasted on this is absolutely wild.\n\nIt is dumb. The underlying pull-req is months old, and people have been expecting v24.0 to be released with some form of full-rbf available for quite some time. Full-rbf is widely believed to be _well_ overdue, and has been held up for entirely political reasons by a small minority of people doing clearly dangerous things.\n\nSuddenly pulling it entirely â even from testnet! â just prior to release is surprising a lot of people. Especially given how weak the argument for pulling it is.\n\nNo one has made a technical argument as to how how releasing a default off feature is harmful.\n\n>Not shipping `mempoolfullrbf` in 24.0 is not a concession to never shipping it and I personally hope that we see full rbf widely deployed on the network at some point.\n\nIt is absolutely a concession to never shipping it.\n\nThis pull-req proposes to remove a default off feature. If even _that_ can't get shipped, in a months long process, what on earth can?\n\n>**If you want the `mempoolfullrbf` option, just run rc3!**\n\nWhy are we pushing people to run release candidates without full support and bug fixes? As discussed above, people have good reasons to run full-rbf in production. And indeed, are running full-rbf in production. Why are we taking steps to prevent people from easily doing that?\n",
